# Title
Paul loves Paula, but Paula loves another (short "a" in alium) / garlic (long "a" in alium).
(Latin: Paulus Paulam amat, sed Paula alium amat.)

## On the phone
### Paul's sweetheart
If it won't be raining, then we will have a party. If it will be raining, then we won't have a party.
(Hungarian: Ha eső nem lesz buli lesz, ha lesz nem lesz.)

### Paul
I well remember the dwarf pantomime actor and his lovers' mime.
(Latin: Bene memini pantomimi minimi et amantium mimi.)

## At home
### Narrator
The potatoes that Paca and Pola are pealing, Pepe is putting, little by little, in piles.
(Spanish: Las papas que pelan Paca y Pola las pone Pepe, poco a poco, en pilas.)

### Paul
Tell me about your purchases! What purchases? About purchases, purchases, your little purchases!
(Russian: Раскажи мне про покупки!
Про какие про покупки?
Про покупки, про покупки, про покупочки твои!)

### Paca
I went to the store and saw a huge potato, went home and was happy.
(Kikuyu: Dathie donyo daria duma dugu dakena dainoka!)



### Paul
Ginseng has to be cut crosswise.
(Latvian or Lettish: Žeņšeņs jāšķērē šķērsām.)

### Sound effect
Chop, put, pack, cut
(Norwegian: Kappe, putte, pakke, kutte)

### Paul
Should we put this yoghurt away after adding garlic to it, or before adding garlic to it?
(Turkish: Bu yoğurdu sarımsaklasak da mı saklasak, sarımsaklamasak da mı saklasak?)

### Paca
If the rabbit takes your garlic away, take the garglic back and cut his claws.
(Italian: Se il coniglio gli agli ti piglia, togligli gli agli a tagliagli gli artigli.)

## In the rain outside Paul's sweetheart's house
### Paul
Since I went out without an umbrella, it would have been better if it had rained earlier.
(French: Etant sorti sans parapluie, il m'eût plus plu qu'il plût plus tôt.)

### (pause)

### Narrator
The frog quacks in the water. German: Der Frosch quakt im Wasser.
(Georgian or Kartveli: ბაყაყი წყალში ყიყინებს)

The spider scratches the frog. The frog scratches the spider. Neither the spider scratches the frog. Nor the frog scratches the spider.
(Portuguese: A aranha arranha a rã. A rã arranha a aranha. Nem a aranha arranha a rã. Nem a rã arranha a aranha.)

### Paul
Rain, rain, The frog doesn't have any ears.
(Czech: Prší, Prší, Žaba nemá uši.)

### (pause)

### Paul
I'm standing in the rain and waiting for you. I'm waiting in the rain an like you.
(German: Ich stehe im Regen und warte auf dich. Ich warte im Regen und steh' auf dich.)

When suffering my only confort was love.
(German: Bei Leid lieh stets Heil die Lieb'.)

### Paula, from her window
How do you want me to like you if the one I want to like me doesn't like me as I want him to like me.
(Spanish: Cómo quieres que te quiera si el que quiero que me quiera no me quiere como quiero que me quiera.)

### Paul
Sometimes when I'm lonely I like talking to feet that smell like horse potoates.
(Xhosa or IsiXhosa: Bu bula booshe bubekxa rubexa roola hoodie hoo.)

### Narrator
Well, it really rains, Paul, but it only rains a little.
(Catalan: Com a ploure, prou que plou, Pau, però plou poc.)
